  1. Tokenize the abstracts and count the number of each token. Do you see anything interesting? Does removing stop words change what tokens appear as the most frequent? What are the 5 most common tokens for each search term after removing stopwords?
pubmed %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%
  count(word) %>%
  top_n(15, n) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, fct_reorder(word, n))) +
  geom_col()

The top used words are stop words. To remove them, we do the following.

pubmed %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = "word") %>%
  filter(!grepl(pattern = "^[0-9]+$", x = word)) %>%
  top_n(5) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = fct_reorder(word,n))) +
    geom_col()
Selecting by n

After removing stop words and numbers, the top five words are covid, patients, cancer, prostate, and disease.

  1. Tokenize the abstracts into bigrams. Find the 10 most common bigrams and visualize them with ggplot2.
pubmed %>%
  unnest_ngrams(word, abstract, n = 2) %>%
  separate (word, c("word1", "word2"),sep = " ") %>%
  anti_join(tidytext::stop_words, by =c("word1" = "word")) %>%
  anti_join(tidytext::stop_words, by =c("word2" = "word")) %>%
  unite(word, word1, word2, sep = " ") %>% 
  count(word, sort = T) %>%
  top_n(10,n) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, fct_reorder(word, n)))+
  geom_col()

The most frequent bigrams are covid 19, prostate cancer, and pre eclampsia.

  1. Calculate the TF-IDF value for each word-search term combination (here you want the search term to be the "document"). What are the 5 tokens from each search term with the highest TF-IDF value? How are the results different from the answers you got in question 1?
pubmed %>%
  unnest_tokens(output = word, input = abstract) %>%
  count(word, term) %>%
  bind_tf_idf(word, term, n) %>%
  arrange(desc(tf_idf)) %>% 
  group_by(term) %>%
  top_n(5,tf_idf) %>%
  arrange(desc(term))
